    "An S-map (φ, f) ∶ a → b induces a by restriction on domain an codomain and function f * ∶ A * → B * defined by f * (a) = f (a)(a ∈ A *).",
    "(φ, f *) is clearly an S-map of domain a * and codomain b *.",
    "Two SG-maps (φ, f) and (φ ′, f ′) with domain a and codomain b are said to be S-equivalent denoted(φ, f) ≡ S (φ ′, f ′) if φ = φ ′ and f * = f ′ *.",
    "The equivalence class of (φ, f) is denoted [φ, f] S.Definition of the category spol• -The objects of the category spol • are p-sites and the morphisms of domain a and codomain b in this category, denoted spol • (a, b), consist of the quotient of the set of all S-maps of domain a and codomain b, with respect to the equivalence relation ≡ S. The association [φ, f] S ↦ (φ, f *) is a bijection of the set spol • (a, b) to the set of SG-maps of domain a * and codomain b *.",
    "The two sets will be identified via this bijection."
